Their theory of the supreme good is at bottom the same, though arrived at in a somewbat different way. The view of man’s development in civilization and the origin of institutions set forth by Lucretius anticipated important modern theorieS, which are by no means confined to the doctrines of materialists, but which, in part at least, have been confirmed by the late investigations of archaeologistS‚ and are generally accepted.²

All that is most valuable and suggestive in Lucretius’ doctrine of the atom has its counterpart in modern science3 and the atomic Materialism of the day, stripped of what belongs not alone to it but to science in general, to theistic as well as to atheistic and agnostic theories of the universe, is precisely Lucretius' doctrine of the nature of thingS, less the blunders in fact and method unavoidable in the state of knowledge of his time. Great as is the scientific value of the doctrine of evolu- tion as a working hypothesis in investigation, as a convenient system of classification for related facts of the organic world, when applied to the explanation of the universe with no God it breaks down utterly. The materialistic evolution of our time, then, is simply the Materialism of Lucretius. wrought over in accordance with the scientific methods and adapted to the scien— tific knowledge of our day. Subjected to the scrutiny of careful criticism‚ it is found to be not a whit nearer to a settlernent of the fundamental questions of existence than the system of the
